  year = {2023},
  abstract = {Negative stiffness (NS) is effective to enhance the control performance of 
  dynamic vibration absorbers (DVAs) on dynamic excitations. Traditional optimal design of 
  NS-DVAs is based on an extension of fixed-point approach, which equalizes the triple fixed 
  points of the dynamic amplification function (DAF) to achieve approximate analytical H∞ 
  optimization for dynamic reduction. However, this leads to an amplification of DAF around 
  the zero frequency, resulting in a significant static amplification effect. For vibration 
  control of purely dynamically excited structures, such as earthquake, the static 
  amplification is neglected. However, for vibrations excited combining static and dynamic 
  components (particularly, wind load), the static amplification may lead to adverse control 
  effect, or even magnify the peak response. In order to avoid this disadvantage, an 
  analytical optimal design approach for inerter-based vibration absorbers (IVAs) with NS 
  (NS-IVAs) is proposed for balancing the static amplification and dynamic reduction effects. 
