  has been obtained. 

By careful selection of the absorber spring stiffness these two saddle points may be adjusted 
to equal elevations. A constant damping curve through either of the saddle points will have a 
horizontal tangent and hence the curve will have a maximum value at a frequency corresponding 
to that of the saddle point. In general, these two curves will correspond to different values 
of relative damping ~'2 and the average value of (2 will be taken as the optimum. In the case 
where the primary damping is zero this procedure leads to results identical with those 
obtained by the procedure of the last paragraph.},
}

@article{nishihara2002closed,
