  publisher = {Elsevier},
  abstract = {In this paper, a real-time hybrid shaking table testing method (RHSTTM) is 
  experimentally implemented for evaluating the performance of a tuned liquid damper (TLD) 
  controlling a seismically excited building structure. The RHSTTM does not require a 
  physical building structural model in performing the experiment of a TLD–structure 
  interaction system and it only uses a TLD and a shaking table. The structural responses of 
  the interaction system are calculated numerically in real time using an analytical building 
  model, a given earthquake record, and a shear force generated by the TLD, and the shaking 
  table reproduces both the controlled and uncontrolled absolute acceleration of the TLD 
  installed floor by modulating the feedback gain of the shear force signal measured by the 
  load-cell positioned between the TLD and the shaking table. Comparison between the 
  structural responses obtained by the RHSTTM and the conventional shaking table test of a 
  single story steel frame with TLD indicates that the performance of the TLD can be 
  accurately evaluated using the RHSTTM without the physical structural model. Finally, the 
  uncontrolled and TLD-controlled structural responses of a three story structure are 
